{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488602","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488602"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:48:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:48:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"489"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"489","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/489"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.11,0.21,0.29,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"489"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96525"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"489","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/489"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"489"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79167"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"8841"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2310"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2399"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32462"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32748"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33085"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39889"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96525","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96525"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset right eye pain after hammering metal pipes at work. He was not wearing safety glasses at the time. He reports intense pain, tearing, and inability to open the affected eye. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed with marked blepharospasm of the right eye. His vital signs are within normal limits. The left eye appears normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Topical anaesthetic","Topical fluorescein","Topical atropine","Computed tomography scan","Urgent ophthalmology referral"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a typical scenario of suspected corneal foreign body or injury from high-velocity metallic particles. The inability to open the eye due to pain (blepharospasm) prevents adequate examination. \u003Cstrong\u003ETopical anaesthetic\u003C/strong\u003E drops are essential as the first step to allow proper examination of the eye. Without adequate pain control and the ability to examine the eye, the nature and severity of the injury cannot be determined.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical fluorescein\u003C/strong\u003E is important for identifying corneal abrasions or foreign bodies, but can only be properly applied and visualised after pain control allows eye opening. Under cobalt blue light, fluorescein will highlight any epithelial defects or trapped foreign bodies. This examination is crucial but must follow initial pain control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical atropine\u003C/strong\u003E is used to provide cycloplegia (paralysis of the ciliary muscle, preventing accommodation) and mydriasis (pupil dilation) in cases of anterior uveitis or after certain eye procedures, but is not appropriate as the first step before examination. It can interfere with proper assessment of pupillary responses and other important examination findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography\u003C/strong\u003E scanning would be indicated if there is suspicion of penetrating eye injury or retained intraocular foreign body, particularly given the mechanism of injury involving high-velocity metallic particles. However, this determination cannot be made without initial examination. Signs suggesting penetrating injury include irregular pupil shape, shallow anterior chamber, or visible penetrating wound.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent ophthalmology referral\u003C/strong\u003E may ultimately be needed depending on the findings, particularly if there are signs of penetrating injury or if foreign body removal is technically challenging. However, initial examination by the emergency physician is required first to determine the severity and nature of the injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter instilling topical anaesthetic drops and achieving adequate pain control, a thorough examination should include visual acuity testing, fluorescein staining, eversion of the eyelids to check for foreign bodies, and careful assessment for signs of penetrating injury. The presence of a metallic foreign body while hammering raises particular concern for possible penetrating injury, which would require urgent ophthalmology consultation if identified. Prevention through appropriate protective eyewear is crucial in avoiding such injuries.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Topical anaesthetic drops are essential for examining painful eyes with suspected foreign bodies or corneal injury.","Safety eyewear should be worn when performing tasks with risk of ocular injury.","Detailed eye examination including fluorescein staining should follow initial pain control.","High-velocity metallic foreign bodies carry risk of penetrating eye injury requiring urgent specialist assessment."],"references":["Bowling, B. (2015). Kanski\u2019s clinical ophthalmology (8th ed.). W B Saunders.","Hendricks BC. Clinical Pearls in Corneal Foreign Body Removal. Review of Optometry. April 15, 2022. Available from: https://www.reviewofoptometry.com/article/clinical-pearls-in-corneal-foreign-body-removal","Fraenkel A, Lee LR, Lee GA. Managing corneal foreign bodies in office-based general practice. Aust Fam Physician. 2017 Mar;46(3):89-93. PMID: 28260265. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28260265/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79167"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"489"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79167","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79167"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-01T20:02:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-01T20:03:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"489"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96525"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"